<ue5><m0>Wanted: New leader<ql>
for wheat board<ql>
<m1><ue5><ep>
<m0> <m0>EDMONTON <m0>(--) The embattled Canadian Wheat Board is looking for a new commissioner after its freshest face resigned over the agency's contentious marketing monopoly.<ep>
   Ken Beswick stepped down Tuesday after locking horns with other commissioners over the monopoly.<ep>
   It's been the cause of a rebellion by a growing number of farmers who want the freedom to market their grain on their own in an effort to get better prices.<ql>
<m1><ql>
<styl>rdup,11p1<ql>
<ue5><m0>Stocks rise amid<ql>
lifted bank issues<ql>
<m1><ue5><ep>
<m0> <m0>TORONTO <m0>(--) Canadian stocks rose as expectations that interest rates will decline lifted bank issues and an asset sale helped Newbridge Networks Corp.'s stock, analysts said.<ep>
   Lower oil and gas shares tempered the index's gains, as crude oil and gas oil prices dropped for a second day on Washington's decision to sell U.S. $227 million of oil reserves to curb rising gas prices.<ep>
   Canadian Imperial Bank of Commerce, Royal Bank of Canada and Bank of Montreal led the Toronto Stock Exchange 300 Composite Index up 4.63 points to 5151.10.<ep>
 The U.S. dollar closed Wednesday at C$1.3610. The Canadian dollar closed Wednesday at U.S. 73.48 cents.<ql>
